2.1 Image Agumentation¶

Image agumentation is a technique to increase the number of training samples/images by applying transformation techniques such as cropping, vertical flipping, changing image saturation, change RGB values and so on. In our report, we have used a popular image agumentation library called Albumentations.

In [ ]:
#composing a transformation object

transform = A.Compose([
    A.HorizontalFlip(p=0.75), #adds horizontal flip 75% of time
    A.VerticalFlip(p=0.75),   #adds vertical flip 75% of time
    A.RandomRotate90(),       #randomly rotates the img
    A.RandomBrightnessContrast(p=0.25), #random brightness change
    A.RGBShift(p=0.30 ),                #random RGB shift
    A.ColorJitter(contrast=0.5,hue=0.2,always_apply=False,p=0.2),
    A.GaussNoise(p=0.20),               #random noise
    
    #add random rain effect to mimic real life scenarios 
    A.RandomRain(p=0.10,blur_value=4, brightness_coefficient=0.5, rain_type= "drizzle"),
  
    #add random sun flare effect 
    A.RandomSunFlare(p=0.10,num_flare_circles_lower=1,num_flare_circles_upper=4, src_radius=200,always_apply=False),
    
    #add random shadow effect
    A.RandomShadow(p=0.15,num_shadows_lower=1, num_shadows_upper=3, shadow_dimension=6, always_apply=False)
])

#helps creating unique id
import uuid


#for following code won't work on Google Colab, it will output error msg here, please ignore
#Img agumentation was done locally


#the following code basically create 10 agumentated images for each image
for i in range(0,10):
    img_name = str(uuid.uuid1())+'.jpg'
    destination = 'agumented/'+img_name
    transformed = transform(image=img)
    img = transformed['image']
    cv2.imwrite(destination, img)
    img_name=''
    img_path=''

As mentioned earlier, please ignore the above error message, if any. The code was written to be run locally and not on Google Colab.

3. Making Changes to the Model Config and Hyperparameters¶

Yolov5 is one of the most popular models used for object detection. As we are utilizing transfer learning, we would have to make certain changes to the model, especially the model's yaml file.

3.1. Creating Custom Configuration YAML File¶

The yaml files are the configuration files of the model. It contains all the necessary "settings" for the model to work properly.

We'll have to create our very own YAML file.

To do so:

3.2. Setting Hyperparameters for training¶

Before we get onto the training we'll have to set the hyperparameters for the training. The final values of hyperparameters have been chosen after running the model through multiple values of hyperpatameters in the prototype phase.

We'll have to create our custom hyperparameter YAML file.

To do so:

We are now in the hyperpatameter folder of the model. We will first create a dictonary to define all the parameters and then write it as a YAML file like we did previously.

There are around 30 hyperparameters for Yolov5. We have only changed the main ones such as optimizer, learning rate, weight deacy and so on. Every other hyperparameter value is set to default.

def get_subtitle(num):
  if num == 0:
    return 'No IED'
  else:
    return 'No of IED detected: ' + str(num)

6.1. Multiple predictions at once¶

There is a folder called 'test' that contains images that have not been used in the training or the validation of the model. The images are completely unseen by the model. We will do our prediction to those images.

In [ ]:
#test imgs path

test_img_path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/MDA522-Ass2/images/test'
In [ ]:
#define a function to load all images from a specific folder


def load_images_from_folder(folder):
    images = []
    for filename in os.listdir(folder):
        img = cv2.imread(os.path.join(folder,filename))
        if img is not None:
            images.append(img)
    return images

#function list of all images from the folder
In [ ]:
#create a list for test images

test_imgs=[]
test_imgs = load_images_from_folder(test_img_path)
len(test_imgs)
Out[ ]:
12

As we can see, we have 12 test images. These images have not been exposed to the model at all.

In [ ]:
#create a list to store all the predicted result from the test
results = []

#loops through each image in the test img list
for img in test_imgs:
  preidcted = model(img)  #does prediction for each img at a time
  
  #adds prediction to the results list
  results.append(preidcted)

len(results)
Out[ ]:
12

The model has done prediction for all 12 of the test images. Now let's plot them.

In [ ]:
%matplotlib inline 

#define rows and columns for the prediction plot
rows = 3
column = 4

#set size
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))

i = 1

#loops through each prediction and plots in a 3x4 grid


for result in results:
  num_ied = len(result.pandas().xyxy[0])
  
  fig.add_subplot(rows, column, i)
  img = np.squeeze(result.render())
  img = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
  plt.title(get_title(num_ied),loc='center', c='red', weight='bold', pad=5)
  plt.ylabel(get_subtitle(num_ied))
  plt.imshow(img)
  i += 1

  #if no. of test images is more than 12 the loop breaks as our plot can only handle 
  #3x4 = 12 charts
  if i >= 13:
    break
    
plt.show()
